{"title_page": "Ann Mercy Hunt", "text_new": "{{short description|(1938\u20132014), medical researcher and campaigner}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ann Mercy Hunt\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 25 October 1938\n| birth_place = [[Welshpool]]\n| death_date  = {{d-da|25 June 2014|25 October 1938}}\n| death_place =\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   = Cambridge University\n| employer    =\n| occupation  = Campaigner\n| spouse      =\n| children    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom]]\n}}\n'''Ann Mercy Hunt''' [[MBE (Order of the British Empire)|MBE]] (25 October 1938 \u2013 25 June 2014) was a [[United Kingdom]] (1938\u20132014), medical researcher and campaigner. She co-founded the '''[[Tuberous Sclerosis Association]]''' and became a researcher into the [[tuberous sclerosis complex]]. Her youngest son died from the condition aged 13. In 1997 the [[TSC2]] gene was identified by a European consortium supported by her organisation.\n\n==Life==\nHunt was born in [[Welshpool]] in 1938. Hunt went to Westminster School for Girls before taking Chemistry at Cambridge University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/jul/30/ann-hunt|title=Ann Hunt obituary|last=McFarlane|first=Isobel|date=2014-07-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nShe had a son who suffered from Tuberous Sclerosis and she was surprised to find that there was so little information or research into the condition.\n\nShe founded the Tuberous Sclerosis Association in 1977.<ref name=tsa>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-109008|title=Hunt [n\u00e9e Carroll], Ann Mercy (1938\u20132014), medical researcher and campaigner {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|website=www.oxforddnb.com|language=en|doi=10.1093/odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-109008|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\nHer youngest son died from the condition aged 13. In 1997 the [[TSC2]] gene was identified by a European consortium supported by her organisation.\n\nIn 2002 she received an MBE for her work with the [[Tuberous Sclerosis Association]].<ref name=tsa/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunt, Ann Mercy}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Welshpool]]\n[[Category:Medical researchers]]\n[[Category:Chemists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|(1938\u20132014), medical researcher and campaigner}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ann Mercy Hunt\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 25 October 1938\n| birth_place = [[Welshpool]]\n| death_date  = {{d-da|25 June 2014|25 October 1938}}\n| death_place =\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   = Cambridge University\n| employer    =\n| occupation  = Campaigner\n| spouse      =\n| children    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom]]\n}}\n'''Ann Mercy Hunt''' [[MBE]] (25 October 1938 \u2013 25 June 2014) was a [[United Kingdom]] (1938\u20132014), medical researcher and campaigner. She co-founded the '''[[Tuberous Sclerosis Association]]''' and became a researcher into the [[tuberous sclerosis complex]]. Her youngest son died from the condition aged 13. In 1997 the [[TSC2]] gene was identified by a European consortium supported by her organisation.\n\n==Life==\nHunt was born in [[Welshpool]] in 1938. Hunt went to Westminster School for Girls before taking Chemistry at Cambridge University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/jul/30/ann-hunt|title=Ann Hunt obituary|last=McFarlane|first=Isobel|date=2014-07-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nShe had a son who suffered from Tuberous Sclerosis and she was surprised to find that there was so little information or research into the condition.\n\nShe founded the Tuberous Sclerosis Association in 1977.<ref name=tsa>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-109008|title=Hunt [n\u00e9e Carroll], Ann Mercy (1938\u20132014), medical researcher and campaigner {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|website=www.oxforddnb.com|language=en|doi=10.1093/odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-109008|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\nHer youngest son died from the condition aged 13. In 1997 the [[TSC2]] gene was identified by a European consortium supported by her organisation.\n\nIn 2002 she received an MBE for her work with the [[Tuberous Sclerosis Association]].<ref name=tsa/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunt, Ann Mercy}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Welshpool]]\n[[Category:Medical researchers]]\n[[Category:Chemists]]\n", "name_user": "Paradoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ann_Mercy_Hunt"}
